        "explanation": "Explanation:\nAll permutations of length 222 are 111-beautiful, thus the first value we print is 2!=22! = 22!=2.\nThere are 161616 222-beautiful permutations out of the 242424 possible permutations. The 888 non-beautiful permutations are: {1,3,2,4},{1,3,4,2},{2,4,1,3},{2,4,3,1},{3,1,2,4},{3,1,4,2},{4,2,1,3},{4,2,3,1}\\{1, 3, 2, 4\\}, \\{1, 3, 4, 2\\}, \\{2, 4, 1, 3\\}, \\{2, 4, 3, 1\\}, \\{3, 1, 2, 4\\}, \\{3, 1, 4, 2\\}, \\{4, 2, 1, 3\\}, \\{4, 2, 3, 1\\}{1,3,2,4},{1,3,4,2},{2,4,1,3},{2,4,3,1},{3,1,2,4},{3,1,4,2},{4,2,1,3},{4,2,3,1}\nFor example, the permutation {1,3,2,4}\\{1, 3, 2, 4\\}{1,3,2,4} is not beautiful as A=[(1\u200amod\u200a2,2\u200amod\u200a2),(3\u200amod\u200a2,4\u200amod\u200a2)]=[(1,0),(1,0)]A = [(1 \\bmod 2, 2 \\bmod 2), (3 \\bmod 2, 4 \\bmod 2)] = [(1, 0), (1, 0)]A=[(1mod2,2mod2),(3mod2,4mod2)]=[(1,0),(1,0)]. Both elements of the array AAA are same."
